The paper deals with submodular maximization, which is a topic in both discrete mathematics and theoretical computer science. The focus on the greedy algorithm and its performance in practice suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. However, the use of optimization concepts such as strong convexity and convergence rates suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-categories. The computational study and empirical results suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Finally, the theoretical analysis and proofs suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category.
